recordings.loc: Helgoland
recordings.rmk: Gannetries are noisy places. The recording captures the never-ending clamour of the Gannetry along the northwest cliffs of Helgoland, Germany. This is the 'basic' soundtrack that accompanies activity among the birds themselves. A variety of actions raise the intensity of calling, such as the arrival of incoming Gannets or a dispute among those already present. The sound is deep and somewhat like that of a Raven but unlike a Raven the 'beat' goes on and on: urrah, urrah, urrah. There is a rising and falling quality to the overall delivery but the notes stay pretty much the same. Although it is possible to distinguish bursts that are higher-pitched (0:08) and lower-pitched (0:21), differences probably reflect the mood of each caller rather than relating to sex differences in the quality of calls. Apparently, in other members of the gannet family (such as Australasian and African Gannet) there is a detectable difference (the male is higher pitched). For more discussion about voice, read THE GANNET by Bryan Nelson (pages 39 & 40).
